Introduction at Savatthi.
The Venerable Radha, seated to one side, said this to the Blessed One: "It would be good for me, venerable sir, if the Blessed One would teach me the Dhamma in brief, so that having heard the Dhamma from the Blessed One, I might dwell alone, secluded, diligent, ardent, and resolute."

"Radha, whatever is of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned. And what, Radha, is of the nature to cease? Form, Radha, is of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned. Feeling is of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned. Perception is of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned. Mental formations are of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned. Consciousness is of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned. Whatever, Radha, is of the nature to cease; in that your desire should be abandoned, your passion should be abandoned, your desire and passion should be abandoned."

The Third Chapter, Request.
Summary:
Mara and Mara-phenomena;
The other two with impermanence;
And two are declared with suffering;
And similarly with non-self;
Waning, passing away, arising;
Twelve with the nature of cessation.
